#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1011
msgid ""
"Next is the type and encoding fields.  It's worth noting that although "
"these field are optional, they are automatically inferred from other "
"information provided.  See `Inference Rules`_ for the algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1023
msgid "type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1016
msgid ""
"A string that describes the type of the data.  Default types are "
"``\"plain\"`` for text data and ``\"binary\"`` for binary data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1019
msgid ""
"There are text types such as ``markdown`` and binary types such as "
"``jpeg`` and ``png``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1022
msgid ""
"If this is not provided, then it defaults to ``\"plain\"`` or "
"``\"binary\"`` based on how the data is provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1028
msgid "encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1026
msgid ""
"A string that is either ``\"binary\"`` or an encoding supported by the "
"Python module ``codec``.  If this is not provided, then it defaults to "
"`\"utf-8\"` or ``\"binary\"`` based on how the data is provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1030
msgid ""
"Here are some rules on how `type` and `encoding` are inferred, if they're"
" not provided:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1033
msgid ""
"If data is given by the key ``\"data\"`` without ``\"data-encoding\"``, "
"then by default, ``type = \"plain\"``, ``encoding = \"utf-8\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1036
msgid ""
"Actually ``encoding = \"utf-8\"`` is not a default, but rather a strict "
"requirement.  This is because strings in Python 3 are UTF-8 strings "
"internally, and so it would only make sense if the encoding is UTF-8 too "
"to reflect that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1041
msgid ""
"Providing an encoding other than ``\"utf-8\"`` will cause the program to "
"issue a ``logging.WARNING`` level of log and the encoding is treated as "
"``\"utf-8\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1045
msgid ""
"If data is given by the key ``\"input\"`` or by keys ``\"data\"`` and "
"`\"data-encoding\"` together, then by default (when neither ``type`` or "
"`encoding` is provided) ``type = \"binary\"``, ``encoding = \"binary\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1049
msgid ""
"This gets a little more complicated when the input path has an extension "
"we can extract with ``os.path.splitext``.  Of course, the main motivation"
" for this inference is that we don't want to provide the same kind of "
"information twice.  When we input from a file with a ``.jpg`` or "
"``.jpeg`` extension, we know that it is a JPEG file and so we shouldn't "
"need to write ``\"type\": \"jpeg\"`` again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1056
msgid ""
"When the file has extension and the program can *infer* the type from it,"
" then ``type`` is set to that inferred type, and `encoding` is either set"
" to ``\"utf-8\"`` or ``\"binary\"``, depending on whether the inferred "
"type is of text or binary type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1061
msgid "Some more optional fields:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1067
msgid "format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1064
msgid ""
"The format of the data, typically accompanied by ``type``.  For example, "
"when we have a ``type`` of ``\"markdown\"`` and ``format`` of "
"``\"pandoc\"``, then we're saying that the Markdown file should be "
"interpreted with `pandoc`_'s default format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1075
msgid "type-format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1072
msgid ""
"Shorthand for providing `type` and `format`. ``\"type-format\": "
"\"TYPE_STRING-FORMAT_STRING\"`` is equivalent to ``\"type\": "
"\"TYPE_STRING\", \"format\": \"FORMAT_STRING\"``, where the hyphen "
"character `-` separates the two."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1079
msgid "caption"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1078
msgid ""
"Short caption/alt text for the data.  Can be a string or a list of "
"strings.  Defaults to ``None``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1082
msgid ""
"A string of a question preceding the block of text written by the user. "
"Defaults to ``None``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1085
msgid "See `Insight and Question`_ for reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1089
msgid "insight"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1088
msgid ""
"A boolean indicating whether this entry is an insight (see `Insight and "
"Question`_ too for reference).  Defaults to ``False``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1120
msgid "meta"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1092
msgid ""
"Metadata.  Currently this can be any ``dict`` with no restriction "
"whatsoever, but the following attributes specifically will be parsed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1095
msgid ""
"``created``: Creation time of a file as a string.  For a photo, this "
"would also be the time it was taken at.  Should be a valid string when "
"passed to ``datetime.datetime.fromisoformat``, and if the result is a "
"naive time object, replaces ``tzinfo`` with that of ``self.date_time``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1100
msgid ""
"Defaults to `None`, which means that the creation date is unknown or this"
" piece of information doesn't make sense here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1103
msgid ""
"This time should be no later than the time provided through the ``date-"
"time``/``time`` field, otherwise an ``InvalidEntryError`` exception is "
"raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1107
msgid ""
"``posted``: Time that this entry was posted at as a string.  Note that "
"this is reserved specifically to the time that is displayed on the "
"Perspective app.  This key is useful when the entry was posted much much "
"later than when it was actually written (e.g. |nbsp| when I wasn't with "
"my phone and could only write on my notebook or type on my laptop)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1114
msgid "Format requirements is similar to that of ``created``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1116
msgid ""
"This time should be no earlier than the time provided through the ``date-"
"time``/``time`` field, otherwise an ``InvalidEntryError`` exception is "
"raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/basicproc/zero.rst:1120
msgid ""
"``desc``: Description.  This key is provided very commonly but "
"surprisingly there's no validation???  ``None`` by default."
msgstr ""

